%%%% agent.dlv — a recursive agent loop, written as an answer set.
%%%%
%%%% The Lisp agent's loop is a recursive FUNCTION over a growing list of
%%%% messages. In DLV there are no functions and no recursion-with-side-
%%%% effects: there are only facts and the models they entail. So the loop's
%%%% one decision — "did the model ask for tools, or did it answer?" — is not
%%%% coded, it is DERIVED. The host writes the latest model turn as facts,
%%%% runs this program, and reads the single answer set back out.
%%%%
%%%% Input facts (written by the host, one turn at a time):
%%%%   tool_call(Id, Name).   % the model requested tool Name with call-id Id
%%%%
%%%% Output (the host filters for -filter=recurse,stop):
%%%%   recurse.               % at least one tool was requested -> run and recur
%%%%   stop.                  % no tools -> the model answered in words; halt
%%%%   run(Id, Name).         % (also derived) the concrete tools to execute

% Recursive case: the model asked for tools.
recurse :- tool_call(_, _).

% Base case: it answered in words. (Negation as failure = the base case.)
stop :- not recurse.

% The tools to run this turn are exactly the ones requested.
run(Id, Name) :- tool_call(Id, Name).

% The agent only knows one tool: a live DLV solver. Anything else is refused.
unknown_tool(Id, Name) :- tool_call(Id, Name), Name != "dlv_solve".
